COURSES.name: Introduction to Digital Arts and Sciences
COURSES.description: Synergy between art and computing through a programming-oriented exploration of fundamental concepts in multimedia.

COURSES.name: Introduction to Computer-Aided Modeling
COURSES.description: Introduces topics related to computer-aided modeling. Polygonal mesh, NURBS and subdivision surface meshes. Materials and shading networks. Lighting, shadows and rendering.

COURSES.name: Artificial Intelligence and Heuristics
COURSES.description: Introduces artificial intelligence concepts. Heuristic search, clause form logic, knowledge representation, reasoning and inference, overview of computer vision, planning, natural language, Lisp and Prolog. (M)

COURSES.name: Computational Structures in Computer Graphics
COURSES.description: Studies the major topics in computer graphics: display and output technology, two and three dimensional manipulations; space curves and surfaces, hidden surface removal and shading models.

COURSES.name: Introduction to Computer Organization
COURSES.description: Organization of computing systems. Logical basis of computer structure. Machine representation of instructions and data, flow of control, and basic machine instructions. Assembly language programming. (M)
COURSES.prerequisites: Credits: 3; Prereq: COP 3504 or COP 3503; and MAC 2233, MAC 2311 or MAC 3472.

COURSES.name: Computer Architecture
COURSES.description: Introduces computer architecture and system organization including virtual memory supports cache, pipeline, vector processing, multiprocessor and RISC architecture.

COURSES.name: Introduction to Software Engineering
COURSES.description: Topics include software planning, specifications, coding, testing and maintenance. Gain experience in the team approach to large system development. (M)

COURSES.name: Computer and Information Science and Engineering Design 1
COURSES.description: Preparatory skills are developed for CISE Design 2 for Computer Engineering students. Teams design, produce and report on a software prototype, meeting defined specifications and using a structured design methodology and project management.

COURSES.name: Human-Computer Interaction
COURSES.description: Studies the major topics in the study, planning and design of the interaction between people and computers. Topics include interface design (principles, theories and guidelines), virtual environments, interactive devices and collaboration.

COURSES.name: User Experience Design
COURSES.description: Introduces methods and tools used in User Experience Design (UXD): the early stages of software design focused on meeting user needs. Key concepts include user research, contextual design, design thinking, ideation, iterative design, prototyping, and design documentation. Projects utilize software tools used in the industry.

COURSES.name: Computer and Information Science and Engineering Design 2
COURSES.description: Involves completing a significant CEN-related project. Coordinate with the instructor and a project advisor, prepare a detailed technical report and deliver an oral presentation.

COURSES.name: Math, Art and Computing
COURSES.description: Introduces interdisciplinary computer science topics. Logic, discrete structures, algorithms and automa. Exploration of topics relating mathematics and computing to art, music and nature. (M)

COURSES.name: Computers and Modern Society
COURSES.description: Impact of computers on society. Discussion includes specific cases from many areas, but does not include problem solution. Does not teach how to use the computer but gives an understanding of the implications of computers. (S) (WR)

COURSES.name: Legal and Social Issues in Computing
COURSES.description: Explores the history, the myth, the ethics, the law and the risks of computer-based technology in modern society. Emphasizes critical analysis of hypotheticals and case studies. Published material is supplemented with online references.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: previous experience in Unix environment.

COURSES.name: Penetration Testing: Ethical Hacking
COURSES.description: Introduces principles and techniques associated with the cybersecurity practice known as penetration testing or ethical hacking. Covers planning, reconnaissance, scanning, exploitation, post-exploitation, and result reporting. Discover how system vulnerabilities can be exploited and learn to avoid such problems.

COURSES.name: Information and Database Systems 1
COURSES.description: First part of a two-course sequence that studies the essential concepts, principles and techniques of modern database systems. Topics include modeling and querying of data using conceptual data models as well as the development of a database application. (M)
COURSES.prerequisites: Credits: 3; Prereq: COP 3504, or COP 3503 and COT 3100.

COURSES.name: Computer and Information Security
COURSES.description: Covers systematic threat and risk assessment; programmed threats and controls in hardware, software, and human procedures; security policies, models, and mechanisms; theoretical limitations and practical implementations; certification and accreditation standards; and case study reviews. Includes projects.

COURSES.name: Introduction to Cryptology
COURSES.description: Introduces classical and modern cryptography and cryptanalysis, including symmetric and asymmetric (public key) ciphers. Covers cryptographic hash functions, block and stream ciphers, as well as differential and linear cryptanalysis. Reviews applications of cryptography, cryptographic standards and protocols, and analyzes case studies of failed implementations.

COURSES.name: Individual Study in CISE
COURSES.description: Problems in different areas of computer science.

COURSES.name: Integrated Product and Process Design 1
COURSES.description: First part of a two-course sequence where teams of engineering and business students partner with industry sponsors to design and build authentic products and processes. Working closely with an industry liaison engineer and a faculty coach, students gain practical experience in teamwork and communication, problem solving and engineering design, and develop leadership, management and people skills. Weekly workshop activities adapt lecture topics to individual projects. Learn firsthand how to develop products and processes that meet customer requirements on time and within budget.
COURSES.prerequisites: Credits: 3; Prereq: CDA 3101, COP 3530, COT 3100 and instructor permission.

COURSES.name: Senior Project
COURSES.description: Involves completing a significant CISE-related project. Coordinate with the instructor and a project advisor, prepare a detailed technical report and deliver an oral presentation. (M)
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: senior CISE standing and approved project proposal.

COURSES.name: Special Topics in CISE
COURSES.description: Variable content provides an opportunity for in-depth study of topics not offered elsewhere and of topics of current significance.

COURSES.name: Practical Work
COURSES.description: One term practical software engineering work under industrial supervision as set forth in the Herbert Wertheim College of Engineering regulations. (S-U)

COURSES.name: Co-Op Work in CISE
COURSES.description: Practical engineering work under industrial supervision, as set forth in the Herbert Wertheim College of Engineering regulations. (S-U)

COURSES.name: Computer Network Fundamentals
COURSES.description: Fundamental concepts, principles and standards of computer networks. Topics are introduced in bottom-up approach, starting from physical layer in OSI system architecture with a stronger focus on data link, mac, network and transport layers. (M)

COURSES.name: Computer Programming Using JAVA
COURSES.description: In-depth treatment of computer programming using JAVA. Problems related to a variety of disciplines are solved. Introduces the basic concepts of software and hardware; develop a variety of stand-alone applications and applets. For non-CISE majors only.

COURSES.name: Computer Programming Using C
COURSES.description: Solve problems related to a variety of disciplines; introduces the basic concepts of software and hardware. (M)

COURSES.name: Programming Fundamentals 1
COURSES.description: First course of a two-semester introductory sequence for those planning further study in computer science, digital arts and sciences or computer engineering. Concepts of computer science and the process of computer programming, including object-oriented programming, procedural and data abstraction and program modularity.

COURSES.name: Programming Fundamentals 2
COURSES.description: Second course of a two-semester introductory sequence for those planning further study in computer science, digital arts and sciences or computer engineering. Concepts of computer science and the process of computer programming, including object-oriented programming, procedural and data abstraction and program modularity.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: COP 3502 with a minimum grade of C or an AP exam in computer science with a minimum grade of 4; and MAC 2311 with a minimum grade of C.

COURSES.name: Data Structures and Algorithm
COURSES.description: Algorithm development using pseudo languages, basic program structures, program design techniques, storage and manipulation of basic data structures like arrays, stacks, queues, sorting and searching and string processing. Linked linear lists. Trees and multilinked structures. (M)
COURSES.prerequisites: Credits: 4; Prereq: COP 3504 or COP 3503 with minimum grade of C, COT 3100, and MAC 2234, MAC 2312, MAC 3473 or MAC 3512.

COURSES.name: Operating Systems
COURSES.description: Design and implementation of various components of a modern operating system, including I/O programming, interrupt handling, process and resource management, computer networks and distributed systems. (M)
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: CDA 3101 and COP 3530; knowledge of C or C++ recommended.
